'''Declan Rice''' (born 14 January 1999) is an English professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[defensive midfielder]] for [[Premier League]] club [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] and the [[England national football team|England national team]]. Known for his versatility, stamina, ball-carrying and tackling,<ref name=":2" /><ref name=":3" /> he is considered one of the best midfielders in the world.<ref>{{cite web |last=Roberts |first=Olly |date=23 June 2023 |title=Ranking the best defensive midfielders in the world from 'Ballon d'Or worthy' to 'past it now' |url=https://www.givemesport.com/ranking-the-15-best-defensive-midfielders-in-the-world-ft-rice-rodri-caicedo/ |access-date=30 July 2024 |website=GiveMeSport}}</ref><ref name=":2">{{cite web |date=16 March 2020 |title=The 25 best defensive midfielders in world football – ranked |url=https://www.90min.com/posts/the-25-best-defensive-midfielders-in-world-football-ranked |access-date=1 April 2025 |website=90min}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=4 June 2024 |title=2024 FC 100: Odegaard among best midfielders in men's soccer |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/40179265/2024-fc-100-martin-odegaard-best-midfielders-men-soccer |access-date=31 July 2024 |website=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=16 April 2025 |title=Declan Rice: Arsenal star cements place as one of world's best midfielders in win over Real Madrid |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cn5xq60k20wo |access-date=20 April 2025 |work=BBC Sport}}</ref>

Rice began his professional career at [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]], having been released by [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]'s [[Chelsea F.C. Development Squad and Academy|academy]], and established himself as a key first-team player by 2017. In 2022, he succeeded [[Mark Noble]] as [[Captain (association football)|club captain]], and led the club to a [[UEFA Europa Conference League]] title the following year, as well as being named the competition's Player of the Season. After making 245 appearances for West Ham, Rice was signed by Arsenal in July 2023 for a club record fee of £100 million, making him the [[List of most expensive association football transfers|joint-most-expensive English player]] in history and going on to help them win their first [[Premier League]] title in 22 years.

Eligible to play for England or the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]], Rice represented the latter internationally at both youth and senior levels prior to 2019. He subsequently changed his national allegiance and made himself available for selection by England. Rice made his England debut in 2019 and was included in the squads for [[UEFA Euro 2020]], the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]], [[UEFA Euro 2024]] and the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]], finishing runner-up in both European Championship editions he participated in.

==Early life and career==
Declan Rice<ref>{{Cite web |date=2 February 2018 |title=Updated squads for 2017/18 Premier League confirmed |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/612828 |access-date=18 February 2018 |publisher=Premier League |archive-date=2 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202113600/https://www.premierleague.com/news/612828 |url-status=live}}</ref> was born on 14 January 1999<ref>{{Cite web |title=D. Rice: Summary |url=https://uk.soccerway.com/players/declan-rice/408158/ |access-date=12 April 2020 |website=Soccerway |publisher=Perform Group |archive-date=9 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190709140337/https://uk.soccerway.com/players/declan-rice/408158/ |url-status=dead}}</ref> in [[Kingston upon Thames]], Greater London, to father Sean and mother Stephanie.<ref>{{cite web |last=O'Hehir |first=Paul |title=Ireland's Declan Rice looks to an unlikely friend for guidance |url=https://www.irishmirror.ie/sport/soccer/soccer-news/declan-rice-looks-good-friend-12214311 |website=[[Irish Mirror]] |access-date=8 January 2026 |date=20 March 2018}}</ref><ref name="Law-2021">{{cite web |last=Law |first=Matt |title=The making of Declan Rice: Tears at Chelsea axe, stand-up comedy - and how Pellegrini helped him commit to England |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/euro-2021/0/declan-rice-england-squad-euros-football-player-euro-team/ |url-access=subscription |website=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |access-date=8 January 2026 |date=13 June 2021}}</ref> He has two older brothers, Connor and Jordan.<ref>{{cite web |last=Rice |first=Declan |title=Declan Rice's grassroots story |url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2022/Nov/07/england-declan-rice-grassroots-football-story-20220711 |website=[[The Football Association]] |access-date=8 January 2026 |date=7 November 2022}}</ref> His paternal grandparents were from [[Douglas, Cork|Douglas]], County Cork, in Ireland.<ref>{{Cite news |last=McDonnell |first=Daniel |date=20 March 2018 |title=Declan Rice: 'There's no decision to be made. If I didn't want to be playing for Ireland, I wouldn't be here' |newspaper=[[Irish Independent]] |location=Dublin |url=https://www.independent.ie/sport/soccer/international-soccer/declan-rice-theres-no-decision-to-be-made-if-i-didnt-want-to-be-playing-for-ireland-i-wouldnt-be-here-36723118.html |access-date=7 September 2018 |archive-date=7 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907183000/https://www.independent.ie/sport/soccer/international-soccer/declan-rice-theres-no-decision-to-be-made-if-i-didnt-want-to-be-playing-for-ireland-i-wouldnt-be-here-36723118.html |url-status=live}}</ref> He began playing football at Dickerage Lane Adventure Playground in Kingston.<ref name="Law-2021" /><ref>{{cite web |last=Pengelly |first=Emma |title=The Kingston YMCA Declan Rice calls his 'second home' |url=https://www.getsurrey.co.uk/sport/football/kingston-ymca-declan-rice-calls-20999729 |website=[[Surrey Live]] |access-date=8 January 2026 |date=8 July 2021}}</ref>

In 2006, he joined the [[Chelsea F.C. Development Squad and Academy|Chelsea F.C. Academy]] as a seven-year-old, where he befriended future England teammate [[Mason Mount]].<ref name="Law-2021" /><ref>{{Cite news |last=Nash |first=Matthew |date=9 November 2018 |title=West Ham's Declan Rice on his rapid rise and future plans with club and country |newspaper=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |location=London |url=https://www.metro.news/west-hams-declan-rice-on-his-rapid-rise-and-future-plans-with-club-and-country/1302609/ |access-date=10 November 2018 |archive-date=11 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181111044010/https://www.metro.news/west-hams-declan-rice-on-his-rapid-rise-and-future-plans-with-club-and-country/1302609/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Northcroft |first=Jonathan |date=2 September 2018 |title=Ireland anger over England's move for Declan Rice |newspaper=[[The Times]] |location=London |url=https://www.thetimes.com/sport/football/article/ireland-anger-over-englands-move-for-declan-rice-zsgt6b05f |url-access=limited |access-date=7 September 2018 |archive-date=7 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907144905/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/ireland-anger-over-englands-move-for-declan-rice-zsgt6b05f |url-status=live}}</ref> In 2013, after his release at age 14, he joined the [[West Ham United F.C. Under-21s and Academy|West Ham United Academy]] after a trial period in the spring.<ref>{{cite web |title=West Ham United Club Statement |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/west-ham-united-club-statement |website=[[West Ham United F.C.]] |access-date=8 January 2026 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230715073248/https://www.whufc.com/news/west-ham-united-club-statement |archive-date=15 July 2023 |date=15 July 2023 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=A personal message to West Ham United supporters from Declan Rice… |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/personal-message-west-ham-united-supporters-declan-rice |website=[[West Ham United F.C.]] |access-date=15 July 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230715072920/https://www.whufc.com/news/personal-message-west-ham-united-supporters-declan-rice |archive-date=15 July 2023 |date=15 July 2023 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Academy coach [[Trevor Bumstead]] stated it was Rice's determination and persistence that helped him break through the ranks at West Ham.<ref>{{cite news |last=Baldi |first=Ryan |date=5 June 2021 |title=Declan Rice: How England midfielder overcame rejection to become key Euro 2020 figure |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/england/57356721 |access-date=22 November 2022 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |language=en-GB}}</ref> Rice won the [[Premier League Cup (football)|Premier League Cup]] in [[2015–16 Under-21 Premier League Cup|2016]] with the under-21s and the [[Professional Development League|Premier League 2 Division 2]] in [[2019–20 Professional U23 Development League|2020]] with the under-23s.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rice: Football is all about trophies |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2017/december/19-december/rice-football-all-about-trophies |website=[[West Ham United F.C.]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171221095107/https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2017/december/19-december/rice-football-all-about-trophies |archive-date=21 December 2017 |date=19 December 2017 |url-status=dead |access-date=9 June 2023}}</ref>

==Club career==
===West Ham United===
====2015–2020====
[[File:Hertha BSC vs. West Ham United 20190731 (191).jpg|thumb|upright|Rice playing for [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] in 2019]]

On 16 December 2015, two years after joining West Ham United at youth level, Rice signed his first professional contract with the club.<ref>{{Cite web |date=28 December 2018 |title=Declan Rice: A career timeline |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2018/december/28-december/declan-rice-career-timeline |access-date=28 December 2018 |publisher=West Ham United F.C. |archive-date=29 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181229031200/https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2018/december/28-december/declan-rice-career-timeline |url-status=live}}</ref> Rice received his first call-up to the West Ham senior squad for the games against [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] and [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] in April 2017, after impressing in the under-23 team.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Inkersole |first=Sam |date=9 May 2017 |title=EXCLUSIVE: Declan Rice says he will stay level headed despite West Ham call-up |url=http://www.football.london/west-ham-united-fc/players/exclusive-declan-rice-says-stay-13007172 |access-date=22 May 2017 |website=football.london |archive-date=8 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190408101410/https://www.football.london/west-ham-united-fc/players/exclusive-declan-rice-says-stay-13007172 |url-status=live}}</ref> He made his senior debut against [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] on the last day of the [[2016–17 Premier League]] season, coming on as a 91st-minute substitute for [[Edimilson Fernandes]] in a 2–1 away win,<ref>{{cite news |last=Emons |first=Michael |date=21 May 2017 |title=Burnley 1–2 West Ham United |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39912028 |access-date=21 May 2017 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |language=en-GB |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170521073225/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39912028 |archive-date=21 May 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Rice&nbsp;– It's a dream come true |url=http://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2017/may/22-may/rice-its-dream-come-true |access-date=22 May 2017 |publisher=West Ham United F.C. |archive-date=1 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180401004629/http://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2017/may/22-may/rice-its-dream-come-true |url-status=live}}</ref> five days after captaining the under-23s to promotion with a 2–1 win away to [[Newcastle United F.C. Reserves and Academy|Newcastle United]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=16 May 2017 |title=Newcastle United v West Ham United |url=https://www.whufc.com/fixtures/first-team/fixtures-and-results/season-20162017/newcastle-united-vs-west-ham-united-1 |access-date=18 August 2017 |publisher=West Ham United F.C. |archive-date=18 August 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170818214244/https://www.whufc.com/fixtures/first-team/fixtures-and-results/season-20162017/newcastle-united-vs-west-ham-united-1 |url-status=live}}</ref> His [[First team (association football)|first-team]] debut came on 19 August 2017 in a 3–2 defeat at [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Inkersole |first=Sam |date=19 August 2017 |title=Revealed:Rice starts for West Ham against Southampton and Antonio returns |url=http://www.football.london/west-ham-united-fc/fixtures-results/revealed-declan-rice-starts-west-13500341 |access-date=24 August 2017 |website=football.london |archive-date=6 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180906055638/https://www.football.london/west-ham-united-fc/fixtures-results/revealed-declan-rice-starts-west-13500341 |url-status=live}}</ref> In April 2018, Rice was named as runner-up for the 2017–18 [[West Ham United F.C.#Hammer of the Year|Hammer of the Year]] award behind [[Marko Arnautović]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Arnautovic crowned Betway Hammer of the Year |url=http://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2018/april/25-april/arnautovic-crowned-betway-hammer-year |publisher=West Ham United F.C. |access-date=26 April 2018 |archive-date=26 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180426144900/http://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2018/april/25-april/arnautovic-crowned-betway-hammer-year |url-status=live}}</ref>

On 22 December 2018, he made his 50th appearance for West Ham,<ref>{{cite web |title=Declan Rice: My 2018/19 West Ham United season |website=[[West Ham United F.C.]] |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2019/may/17-may/declan-rice-my-201819-west-ham-united-season |access-date=1 April 2025 |date=17 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819184328/https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2019/may/17-may/declan-rice-my-201819-west-ham-united-season |archive-date=19 August 2019 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Williams |first=Jay |date=23 December 2018 |title='What an achievement' – West Ham fans congratulate Rice on 50 appearances |url=https://www.hammers.news/club-news/what-an-achievement-west-ham-fans-congratulate-rice-on-50-appearances/ |access-date=1 April 2025 |website=Hammers News |language=en-GB}}</ref> becoming the first player to do so while still a teenager since [[Michael Carrick]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Inkersole |first=Sam |date=15 November 2018 |title=Mason's ironic cheers & Rice going mad – West Ham moments missed |url=https://www.football.london/west-ham-united-fc/fixtures-results/masons-ironic-cheers-holebass-clearance-15588611 |access-date=30 December 2018 |website=football.london |archive-date=30 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181230081133/https://www.football.london/west-ham-united-fc/fixtures-results/masons-ironic-cheers-holebass-clearance-15588611 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=29 December 2018 |title=Analysis: Resilient Rice has shown age is no barrier |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2018/december/29-december/analysis-resilient-rice-has-shown-age-no-barrier |access-date=30 December 2018 |publisher=West Ham United F.C. |archive-date=30 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181230080924/https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2018/december/29-december/analysis-resilient-rice-has-shown-age-no-barrier |url-status=live}}</ref> On 28 December 2018, Rice signed a new contract until 2024 with the option of an additional year.<ref>{{Cite web |title=West Ham United sign Declan Rice to new long-term contract |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2018/december/28-december/west-ham-united-sign-declan-rice-new-long-term-contract |access-date=29 December 2018 |publisher=West Ham United F.C. |archive-date=29 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181229013712/https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2018/december/28-december/west-ham-united-sign-declan-rice-new-long-term-contract |url-status=live}}</ref> On 12 January 2019, Rice scored his first goal for West Ham and was named [[man of the match]] in a 1–0 win against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], in West Ham's 50th Premier League game at the [[London Stadium]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Johnston |first=Neil |date=12 January 2019 |title=West Ham United 1–0 Arsenal |website=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/46766896 |access-date=18 January 2019 |archive-date=17 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190117192742/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/46766896 |url-status=live}}</ref> On 20 April, Rice was named on the shortlist for the [[PFA Young Player of the Year]] award, which was eventually awarded to Rice's England teammate [[Raheem Sterling]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Morgan |first1=Tom |last2=Whyatt |first2=Katie |date=28 April 2019 |title=Liverpool's Virgil van Dijk rewarded for near-perfect season with PFA Player of the Year award |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/04/28/liverpools-virgil-van-dijk-rewarded-near-perfect-season-pfa/ |access-date=29 April 2019 |work=The Telegraph |language=en-GB |issn=0307-1235 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190428222821/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/04/28/liverpools-virgil-van-dijk-rewarded-near-perfect-season-pfa/ |archive-date=28 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> At the end of the 2018–19 season, he was named the Players' Player of the Year and won the award for Individual Performance of the Season, for his match winning game against Arsenal, and was named the Young Hammer of the Year for the third-consecutive season.<ref>{{Cite web |date=9 May 2019 |title=Delighted Declan Rice wins three Player Awards |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2019/may/09-may/delighted-declan-rice-wins-three-player-awards |access-date=12 September 2020 |publisher=West Ham United F.C. |archive-date=29 September 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200929105054/https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2019/may/09-may/delighted-declan-rice-wins-three-player-awards |url-status=live}}</ref>

On 28 December 2019, Rice captained West Ham for the first time, at age 20, in a 2–1 home loss against [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Team news: Fabianski returns, Reid on bench, Rice named captain |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2019/december/28-december/team-news-fabianski-returns-reid-bench-rice-named-captain |date=28 December 2019|access-date=3 September 2021 |publisher=[[West Ham United F.C.]]|archive-date=2 September 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210902232918/https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2019/december/28-december/team-news-fabianski-returns-reid-bench-rice-named-captain|url-status=dead}}</ref> He scored his first and only Premier League goal of the season on 17 July 2020, with an outside-the-box strike against [[Watford F.C.|Watford]], in a 3–1 win.<ref>{{Cite web |date=18 July 2020 |title=West Ham 3–1 Watford: Hammers close in on Premier League safety |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/west-ham-vs-watford/report/408340 |access-date=27 July 2020 |website=Sky Sports |archive-date=24 July 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200724215119/https://www.skysports.com/football/west-ham-vs-watford/report/408340 |url-status=live}}</ref> In the 2019–20 season, Rice played every minute of West Ham's 38 league games. He was in the Premier League's top five players for both tackles and interceptions, leading West Ham players in both categories and making more passes than any other teammate. He was named [[West Ham United F.C.#Hammer of the Year|Hammer of the Year]] for the first time in 2020.<ref name="hoty1920">{{Cite web |date=26 July 2020 |title=Declan Rice crowned 2019/20 Betway Hammer of the Year |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2020/july/26-july/declan-rice-crowned-201920-betway-hammer-year |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200726185846/https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2020/july/26-july/declan-rice-crowned-201920-betway-hammer-year |archive-date=26 July 2020 |access-date=27 July 2020 |publisher=West Ham United F.C.}}</ref>

====2020–2023====
[[File:Rice UEFA winner.jpeg|thumb|upright|Rice (right) celebrates on the pitch after winning the [[2023 UEFA Europa Conference League final]] with [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]]]

On 15 February 2021, Rice scored his first goal of the season<ref>{{cite web |title=On This Day: Declan Rice's memorable first West Ham United goal |website=[[West Ham United F.C.]] |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/day-declan-rices-memorable-first-west-ham-united-goal |access-date=1 April 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220522195809/https://www.whufc.com/news/day-declan-rices-memorable-first-west-ham-united-goal |archive-date=22 May 2022 |url-status=dead}}</ref> when he converted a penalty and put the team in the lead against [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] in a home league win that ended 3–0.<ref>{{cite news |last=MacInnes |first=Paul |date=15 February 2021 |title=Rice and Diop lead in-form West Ham to win over Sheffield United |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2021/feb/15/west-ham-sheffield-united-premier-league-match-report |access-date=23 February 2021 |work=[[The Guardian]] |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210223183206/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2021/feb/15/west-ham-sheffield-united-premier-league-match-report |archive-date=23 February 2021 |url-status=live}}</ref> In April 2021, having played in all of West Ham's games so far in the [[2020–21 West Ham United F.C. season|2020–21 season]], Rice was ruled out for four weeks with a knee injury picked up on international duty with England.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Stone |first=Simon |date=6 April 2021 |title=Declan Rice: West Ham midfielder to miss four weeks with knee injury |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/56640577 |access-date=6 April 2021 |website=BBC Sport |archive-date=6 April 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210406005216/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/56640577 |url-status=live}}</ref>

On 16 September 2021, Rice made his European debut and scored his debut European goal in a 2–0 away victory over [[GNK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]] in the [[2021–22 UEFA Europa League|Europa League]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Declan Rice: It's an incredible feeling to win in Europe |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2021/september/16-september/declan-rice-its-incredible-feeling-win-europe |publisher=West Ham United F.C. |access-date=16 September 2021 |language=en |date=16 September 2021 |archive-date=16 September 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210916203226/https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2021/september/16-september/declan-rice-its-incredible-feeling-win-europe |url-status=live}}</ref>

On 9 May 2022, Rice was named as Hammer of the Year for a second time.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/it-happened-202122-player-awards-brought-you-betway-aid-academy |title=As It Happened: 2021/22 Player Awards brought to you by Betway in aid of the Academy |publisher=West Ham United F.C. |date=9 May 2022 |access-date=9 May 2022 |archive-date=31 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221031141405/https://www.whufc.com/news/it-happened-202122-player-awards-brought-you-betway-aid-academy |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Declan Rice crowned 2021/22 Betway Hammer of the Year |website=[[West Ham United F.C.]] |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/declan-rice-crowned-202122-betway-hammer-year |access-date=1 April 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220618104833/https://www.whufc.com/news/declan-rice-crowned-202122-betway-hammer-year |archive-date=18 June 2022 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Following West Ham's Europa League campaign, which saw them reach the semi-final, Rice was named in the 2021–22 UEFA Europa League Team of the Year alongside teammate [[Craig Dawson]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/europa-league-team-of-the-season-declan-rice-craig-dawson-rangers-2022-b1001366.html |title=West Ham duo Rice & Dawson named in Europa League team of the Season |first=Jonathan |last=Gorrie |date=20 May 2022 |newspaper=Evening Standard |location=London |access-date=20 May 2022 |archive-date=31 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221031141429/https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/europa-league-team-of-the-season-declan-rice-craig-dawson-rangers-2022-b1001366.html |url-status=live}}</ref> Following the retirement of [[Mark Noble]] in May 2022, Rice was named as captain of West Ham.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football.london/west-ham-united-fc/declan-rice-west-ham-england-24623803 |title=Declan Rice relishing in role as West Ham's captain as he sets England target |first=Jonty |last=Colman |date=29 July 2022 |website=Football.London |access-date=30 July 2022 |archive-date=22 September 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220922005359/https://www.football.london/west-ham-united-fc/declan-rice-west-ham-england-24623803 |url-status=live}}</ref>

On 16 October 2022, Rice opened his goalscoring account for the season,<ref>{{cite web |title=2021/22 Betway Player Awards round-up |website=[[West Ham United F.C.]] |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/202122-betway-player-awards-round |access-date=1 April 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220603125900/https://www.whufc.com/news/202122-betway-player-awards-round |archive-date=3 June 2022 |url-status=dead}}</ref> scoring a curling effort from {{convert|22|yards}} to secure West Ham a point in a 1–1 draw against Southampton.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/goals-southampton-1-1-west-ham-united |title=Goals: Southampton 1–1 West Ham United |date=16 October 2022 |access-date=23 April 2023 |website=West Ham United F.C. |archive-date=23 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230423190732/https://www.whufc.com/news/goals-southampton-1-1-west-ham-united |url-status=live }}</ref> On 20 April 2023, Rice scored West Ham's third in a 4–1 win in the [[UEFA Europa Conference League]] against Belgian side [[K.A.A. Gent|Gent]], carrying the ball for more than {{convert|50|metres|yards}} before finishing past Gent goalkeeper [[Davy Roef]], resulting in a goal labelled "perhaps the standout strike of Rice's career" by ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dean |first1=Sam |last2=Thomas |first2=Harri |date=20 April 2023 |title=West Ham vs Gent result: Declan Rice wonder goal headlines superb fightback |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2023/04/20/west-ham-vs-gent-europa-conference-league-live-latest/ |access-date=23 April 2023 |work=The Telegraph |language=en-GB |issn=0307-1235 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230423190730/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2023/04/20/west-ham-vs-gent-europa-conference-league-live-latest/ |archive-date=23 April 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref>

In May 2023, he was again named Hammer of the Year, for the [[2022–23 West Ham United F.C. season|2022–23 season]].<ref name="HotY23">{{cite web | title=Declan Rice crowned Betway Hammer of the Year for 2022/23 | website=West Ham United F.C. | url=http://www.whufc.com/news/declan-rice-crowned-betway-hammer-year-202223 | access-date=22 May 2023 | date=21 May 2023 | archive-date=22 May 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230522114416/https://www.whufc.com/news/declan-rice-crowned-betway-hammer-year-202223 | url-status=live }}</ref> On 8 June 2023, Rice was named as the Europa Conference League's player of the season by [[UEFA]] as Rice captained West Ham to their first major European trophy since 1965 after a 2–1 win against [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]] in the [[2023 UEFA Europa Conference League final|final]] a day prior.<ref name="ConfPOTS">{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaconferenceleague/news/0282-183500452524-1c503bccb2ed-1000--conference-league-player-of-the-season-rice/ |title=Declan Rice named UEFA Europa Conference League Player of the Season |date=8 June 2023 |access-date=8 June 2023 |website=UEFA |archive-date=8 June 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230608135306/https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaconferenceleague/news/0282-183500452524-1c503bccb2ed-1000--conference-league-player-of-the-season-rice/ |url-status=live }}</ref> During the 2022–23 season, Rice won possession more than any other Premier League player. He also made the most interceptions of all Premier League players.<ref>{{cite web |last=Segar |first=David |date=29 June 2023 |title=Why West Ham's Declan Rice is a Wanted Man |url=https://theanalyst.com/articles/declan-rice-arsenal-man-city-transfer |access-date=10 July 2023 |website=Opta Analyst}}</ref>

Rice left West Ham in July 2023, joining [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]. He played 245 games for West Ham, scoring 15 goals. He is one of only three West Ham captains, along with [[Bobby Moore]] and [[Billy Bonds]], to have captained the club to a major trophy.<ref>{{cite web | website=eurosport.co.uk | url=https://www.eurosport.co.uk/football/declan-rice-explains-tough-decision-to-leave-in-emotional-goodbye-to-hammers-fans_sto9701731/story.shtml |title= DECLAN RICE EXPLAINS 'TOUGH DECISION' TO LEAVE IN EMOTIONAL GOODBYE TO WEST HAM FANS AS EXIT CONFIRMED| access-date=16 July 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Power |first=Lee |date=15 July 2023 |title=Rice gives thanks as Hammers departure confirmed |url=https://www.newhamrecorder.co.uk/sport/23657536.declan-rice-gives-thanks-west-ham-united-exit-confirmed/ |access-date=16 July 2023 |website=[[Newham Recorder]]}}</ref> West Ham chairman [[David Sullivan (businessman)|David Sullivan]] said that the club did not want to sell the player, stating that they wished to build the team around him, but that Rice had made it clear he wanted to move on.<ref>{{cite web | last=Sternik | first=Seb | title=We did not want to sell West Hams David Sullivan makes Declan Rice admission amid Arsenal move | website=PlanetSport | date=15 July 2023 | url=https://www.planetsport.com/soccer/news/want-sell-west-ham-david-sullivan-makes-declan-rice-admission-amid-arsenal-move | access-date=16 July 2023}}</ref> Rice said of the transfer: "Ultimately, though, it has only ever been about my ambition to play at the very highest level of the game."<ref>{{cite news |title=Declan Rice confirms 'tough' West Ham departure with Arsenal move imminent |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/west-ham-arsenal-declan-rice-england-rice-b2375828.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241227182926/https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/west-ham-arsenal-declan-rice-england-rice-b2375828.html |archive-date=27 December 2024 |access-date=16 July 2023 |work=The Independent |language=en-GB |url-status=live |date=15 July 2023 |last=Markham |first=Carl}}</ref>

===Arsenal===
====2023–24====
[[File:RC Lens - Arsenal FC (03-10-2023) 23.jpg|thumb|upright|Rice playing for [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in 2023]]

On 15 July 2023, Rice signed for Premier League club Arsenal on a long-term contract.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/declan-rice-completes-transfer-arsenal |title=Declan Rice completes transfer to Arsenal |publisher=Arsenal F.C. |date=15 July 2023 |access-date=15 July 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=15 July 2023 |title=Declan Rice says 'tough' to leave West Ham with Arsenal transfer confirmed |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66209874 |access-date=1 April 2025 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |language=en-GB}}</ref> It was reported that the transfer fee was a club-record initial £100m, potentially rising by £5m, in add-ons, making him the [[List of most expensive association football transfers|most expensive English player]], equalling the previous record held by [[Jack Grealish]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/65982835 |title=Declan Rice: Arsenal sign England midfielder from West Ham for £105m |website=BBC Sport |date=15 July 2023 |access-date=15 July 2023}}</ref> The structure of the transfer was given as West Ham receiving £50m immediately and a further £50m in the summer of 2024. They will also receive £1m every time Arsenal qualify for a place in the [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] during his time at the club and £1m if he plays 60 per cent of games in a season, with those payments capped at £5m.<ref>{{cite news |date=15 July 2023 |title=Breakdown of payment schedule for Declan Rice's Arsenal move revealed |url=https://www.independent.ie/sport/soccer/premier-league/breakdown-of-payment-schedule-for-declan-rices-arsenal-move-revealed/a1692646195.html |access-date=15 July 2023 |newspaper=[[Irish Independent]] |last=Palmer |first=Kevin}}</ref>

Rice made his Arsenal debut on 6 August against [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in the [[2023 FA Community Shield]], which Arsenal won 4–1 on penalties after a 1–1 draw.<ref>{{Cite web |date=6 August 2023 |title=Arsenal 1–1 Man City (4–1 on pens) |work=Sky Sports |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/arsenal-vs-manchester-city/report/482389 |language=en}}</ref> On 12 August, Rice started in Arsenal's opening match of the [[2023–24 Premier League]] season, a 2–1 home win over [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Walker |first=Andrew |date=12 August 2023 |title=Declan Rice's first-half by numbers: Midfielder superb vs. Forest |url=https://www.caughtoffside.com/2023/08/12/declan-rice-arsenal-stats-against-nottingham-forest/ |access-date=12 August 2023 |website=CaughtOffside |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Glendenning |first=Barry |date=12 August 2023 |title=Arsenal 2–1 Nottingham Forest: Premier League – as it happened |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2023/aug/12/arsenal-v-nottingham-forest-premier-league-live |access-date=12 August 2023}}</ref> On 3 September, he scored his first goal for Arsenal, in stoppage time to grant his team a 2–1 lead against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in a match which ended in a 3–1 win.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/sep/03/arsenal-manchester-united-premier-league-match-report |title=Declan Rice late strike earns Arsenal dramatic Manchester United victory |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=3 September 2023 |access-date=3 September 2023}}</ref>

Rice was announced as a nominee for [[The Best FIFA Men's Player]] based on his performances for both London clubs and the national team.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/rice-nominated-best-fifa-mens-player |title=Rice nominated for Best FIFA Men's Player |work=Arsenal FC |date=3 September 2023 |access-date=3 December 2023}}</ref> On 11 February, Rice scored his first goal against his former club, West Ham United, in a 6–0 victory at London Stadium, which was West Ham's worst home defeat in the league since 1963 against [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Mallows |first=Tom |date=11 February 2024 |title=West Ham United 0–6 Arsenal: Gunners romp to emphatic win to close gap on leaders |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/68196268 |access-date=11 February 2024 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

====2024–25====
On 21 December 2024, Rice came off the bench against [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]], scoring and providing an assist to teammate [[Gabriel Martinelli]] in the 5–1 away rout of the ''Eagles''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arsenal.com/fixture/arsenal/2024-Dec-21/crystal-palace-1-5-arsenal-match-report|title=Report: Crystal Palace 1–5 Arsenal|first=Josh|last=James|date=21 December 2024|access-date=8 June 2025|website=Arsenal.com|language=en}}</ref> On 22 January 2025, Rice scored his first [[UEFA Champions League]] goal in 3–0 victory over [[GNK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://onefootball.com/fr/news/arsenal-3-0-dinamo-zagreb-player-ratings-as-declan-rice-scores-first-champions-league-goal-40600604 |title=Arsenal 3–0 Dinamo Zagreb: Player Ratings as Declan Rice Scores First Champions League Goal |publisher=OneFootball |date=22 January 2025 }}</ref> On 8 April, he netted two direct [[free kick]] goals in a 3–0 home win over reigning champions [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] in the first leg of the [[2024–25 UEFA Champions League knockout phase#Quarter-finals|Champions League quarter-finals]],<ref>{{Cite news |last=Howell |first=Alex |date=8 April 2025 |title=Arsenal 3–0 Real Madrid |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cx256773e2yt |access-date=8 April 2025 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> becoming the first player ever to score two free kicks in a Champions League knockout phase match.<ref>{{cite web |title=(VIDEO) Declan Rice's Double Free Kick Wonder Goals with Arsenal to Knock Out Real Madrid in the Champions League |url=https://www.beinsports.com/en-us/soccer/uefa-champions-league/articles-video/-video-declan-rice-s-double-free-kick-wonder-goals-with-arsenal-to-knock-out-real-madrid-in-the-champions-league-2025-04-08 |date=8 April 2025 |access-date=8 April 2025 |website=beIN SPORTS}}</ref> On 18 May, he scored the only goal in a 1–0 win over Newcastle United, securing Arsenal's runner-up finish in the Premier League and qualification for the UEFA Champions League in the following season.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McNicholas |first1=James |last2=Waugh |first2=Chris |title=Arsenal 1 Newcastle 0 – Rice wraps up Champions League spot but Howe's side face final-day shootout |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/6361815/2025/05/18/arsenal-newcastle-rice-arteta-champions-league/ |publisher=The Athletic |access-date=6 June 2025 |date=18 May 2025}}</ref> Following another successful individual campaign with Arsenal, Rice was voted as the [[Arsenal Player of the Season]].<ref>{{cite web|date=6 June 2025|url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/rice-wins-mens-player-season-202425|first=Jonathon|last=Rogers|title=Rice wins men's Player of the Season for 2024/25|access-date=8 June 2025|website=Arsenal|language=en}}</ref> He was also selected in the [[UEFA Champions League#Team of the Season|UEFA Champions League Team of the Season]] by UEFA's Technical Observer Group, and nominated for the [[Premier League Player of the Season]] award.<ref>{{cite web|date=1 June 2025|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/029a-1de594e11846-742ee836b971-1000--2024-25-champions-league-team-of-the-season/|website=UEFA|title=2024/25 Champions League Team of the Season|language=en|access-date=8 June 2025}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=16 May 2025|url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/4309067|website=Premier League|title=EA SPORTS 2024/25 Player of the Season shortlist|access-date=8 June 2025}}</ref>

On 20 June 2025, it was announced that Rice was one of six nominees for the [[PFA Players' Player of the Year]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-06-20 |title=PFA Players' Player of the Year: Bruno Fernandes and Mohamed Salah among nominees |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cx23n4z20j9o |access-date=2025-06-20 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

====2025–26====

On 5 October 2025, Declan Rice scored his first goal of the season against former club [[West Ham United]] in a 2–0 Premier League home win.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Arsenal 2–0 West Ham: Game Analysis |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/report/_/gameId/740656 |website=ESPN |date=4 October 2025 |access-date=5 October 2025}}</ref> On 1 November, he netted in a 2–0 away victory against [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]], earning himself [[Player of the match#Association football|Man of the match]] for his performance.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Report: Burnley 0–2 Arsenal|url=https://www.arsenal.com/fixture/arsenal/2025-Nov-01/burnley-0-2-arsenal-match-report|date=1 November 2025|access-date=6 December 2025|last=Peat|first=Charlie|publisher=Arsenal F.C.}}</ref> On 4 December, he was nominated for the [[2025–26 Premier League#Monthly awards|Premier League Player of the Month]] award for November.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.premierleague.com/en/news/4480883/ea-sports-premier-league-player-of-the-month-november-2025-shortlist|publisher=Premier League|title=Pick your EA SPORTS Player of the Month|date=4 December 2025|access-date=6 December 2025|language=en}}</ref> Rice was an important part of Arsenal winning the [[2025–26 Premier League]] title.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Robson |first=James |date=2026-05-19 |title=Arsenal wins its first Premier League title in 22 years after Man City draws with Bournemouth |url=https://apnews.com/article/man-city-bournemouth-arsenal-premier-league-title-tottenham-828b9b177f8c0484754945eeb4ee0d0f |access-date=2026-05-19 |website=AP News |language=en}}</ref>

==International career==
===Republic of Ireland===
Although born in London, Rice was eligible to play for Ireland as his paternal grandparents are from [[Cork (city)|Cork]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Fallon |first=John |date=5 October 2017 |title=Rice grateful to talent scout O'Toole for helping his swift rise |newspaper=Irish Independent |location=Dublin |url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/soccer/international-soccer/rice-grateful-to-talent-scout-otoole-for-helping-his-swift-rise-36198526.html |access-date=5 October 2017 |archive-date=5 October 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005151319/http://www.independent.ie/sport/soccer/international-soccer/rice-grateful-to-talent-scout-otoole-for-helping-his-swift-rise-36198526.html |url-status=live}}</ref> On 19 March 2017, Rice was named [[Republic of Ireland national under-17 football team|Republic of Ireland U17]] player of the year.<ref name="3fai2">{{Cite web |date=19 March 2017 |title=Winners revealed for Three FAI International Football Awards |url=http://www.fai.ie/ireland/news/winners-revealed-for-three-fai-international-football-awards |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171202103842/http://www.fai.ie/ireland/news/winners-revealed-for-three-fai-international-football-awards |archive-date=2 December 2017 |access-date=24 May 2017 |publisher=Football Association of Ireland}}</ref> On 23 May 2017, only days after his [[Premier League]] debut, Rice was named in the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] squad to play friendlies against [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] and [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] and a World Cup qualifier at home to [[Austria national football team|Austria]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Fitzmaurice |first=Aidan |date=23 May 2017 |title=West Ham teenager Declan Rice called into Ireland senior squad by Martin O'Neill along with Cork duo |newspaper=Irish Independent |location=Dublin |url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/soccer/international-soccer/west-ham-teenager-declan-rice-called-into-ireland-senior-squad-by-martin-oneill-along-with-cork-duo-35747101.html |access-date=24 August 2017 |archive-date=24 August 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170824092628/http://www.independent.ie/sport/soccer/international-soccer/west-ham-teenager-declan-rice-called-into-ireland-senior-squad-by-martin-oneill-along-with-cork-duo-35747101.html |url-status=live}}</ref> He made his senior debut on 23 March 2018 in a 1–0 defeat to [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]].<ref>{{Cite news |date=23 March 2018 |title=New faces fail to inspire Ireland in Turkey |website=The42.ie |url=http://www.the42.ie/ireland-turkey-report-3921212-Mar2018/ |access-date=23 March 2018 |archive-date=23 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180323221707/http://www.the42.ie/ireland-turkey-report-3921212-Mar2018/ |url-status=live}}</ref>

In August 2018, Rice was omitted from the squad to play [[Wales national football team|Wales]] by manager [[Martin O'Neill]], who said that Rice was considering switching to play for [[England national football team|England]] after being approached by them.<ref>{{Cite news |date=27 August 2018 |title=England 'have spoken to' West Ham's Declan Rice, says Martin O'Neill |newspaper=The Guardian |agency=Press Association |location=London |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/aug/27/england-have-spoken-to-declan-rice-martin-oneill-west-ham |access-date=27 January 2019 |archive-date=13 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181213185145/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/aug/27/england-have-spoken-to-declan-rice-martin-oneill-west-ham |url-status=live}}</ref> By November 2018, having been omitted from three squads selected by O'Neill, Rice said he was no closer in deciding whether to play for Ireland or England.<ref>{{Cite web |date=9 November 2018 |title=Declan Rice: Choosing between England and Republic of Ireland not easy |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46153251 |access-date=10 November 2018 |website=BBC Sport |archive-date=10 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181110035310/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46153251 |url-status=live}}</ref> In December 2018, Rice met with new Ireland manager [[Mick McCarthy]] and his assistant, [[Robbie Keane]]. McCarthy said that Rice was a potential future captain of Ireland and that he would build the team around Rice should he decide to play for the country.<ref>{{Cite news |date=23 December 2018 |title=Declan Rice: Republic of Ireland boss Mick McCarthy says West Ham player could be his captain |website=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46666804 |access-date=28 December 2018 |archive-date=25 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181225215022/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46666804 |url-status=live}}</ref>

===England===
[[File:The Prime Minister visits St George's Park on October 10, 2023 (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|Rice with [[England national football team|England]] in 2023]]

On 13 February 2019, Rice pledged his future to England.<ref>{{Cite web |date=13 February 2019 |title=Declan Rice pledges future to England |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/international/declan-rice-england-republic-of-ireland-country-nationality-west-ham-united-gareth-southgate-a8777776.html |access-date=13 February 2019 |newspaper=The Independent |archive-date=14 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190214002657/https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/international/declan-rice-england-republic-of-ireland-country-nationality-west-ham-united-gareth-southgate-a8777776.html |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=18 February 2019 |title=Declan Rice: Is West Ham midfielder ready for England? |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47286157 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=19 February 2019 |archive-date=19 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190219183533/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47286157 |url-status=live}}</ref> On 5 March, his change of allegiance was confirmed by [[FIFA]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=5 March 2019 |title=Declan Rice: Fifa confirms West Ham midfielder's switch to England from Republic of Ireland |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47458759 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=5 March 2019 |archive-date=6 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306044745/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47458759 |url-status=live}}</ref> On 13 March, he was called up by England for their forthcoming [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying]] matches against the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]] and [[Montenegro national football team|Montenegro]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=13 March 2019 |title=Declan Rice: England call-up for West Ham midfielder for Euro 2020 qualifiers |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47551783 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=13 March 2019 |archive-date=13 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190313123209/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47551783 |url-status=live}}</ref> He made his debut on 22 March as a 63rd-minute substitute against the Czech Republic at [[Wembley Stadium]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=McNulty |first=Phil |date=22 March 2019 |title=England 5–0 Czech Republic |website=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47578575 |access-date=23 March 2019 |archive-date=21 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321183435/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47578575 |url-status=live}}</ref>

On 25 March 2019, England manager [[Gareth Southgate]] handed Rice his first start for the national side during a 5–1 victory over Montenegro.<ref>{{Cite web |last=McNulty |first=Phil |date=25 March 2019 |title=Montenegro 1–5 England |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/47606892 |access-date=26 March 2019 |website=BBC Sport |archive-date=26 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190326103836/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/47606892 |url-status=live}}</ref> Following Rice's successful [[2018–19 West Ham United F.C. season|season]], he was handed a place in the [[2019 UEFA Nations League Finals squads#England|England squad]] for the [[2019 UEFA Nations League Finals]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=McNulty |first=Phil |date=27 May 2019 |title=Nations League: England drop Kieran Trippier but Harry Kane included |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48428100 |access-date=27 May 2019 |website=BBC Sport |archive-date=27 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190527201607/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48428100 |url-status=live}}</ref> In September 2019, Rice said that he had received online [[death threat]]s after switching allegiance.<ref>{{Cite web |date=9 September 2019 |title=Declan Rice: I've endured death threats for quitting Ireland |url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/sport/soccer/declan-rice-ive-endured-death-threats-for-quitting-ireland-949760.html |newspaper=Irish Examiner |access-date=10 September 2019 |archive-date=26 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190926150712/https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/sport/soccer/declan-rice-ive-endured-death-threats-for-quitting-ireland-949760.html |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=9 September 2019 |title=Declan Rice: West Ham midfielder reveals he received threats after England switch |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49641824 |access-date=10 September 2019 |website=BBC Sport |archive-date=10 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190910065311/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49641824 |url-status=live}}</ref> He was the first player to play for both countries since [[Jack Reynolds (footballer, born 1869)|Jack Reynolds]] in the 1890s.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Walker |first=Michael |date=9 March 2019 |title=Michael Walker: before Declan Rice, only one man had played for Ireland and England |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/soccer/international/michael-walker-before-declan-rice-only-one-man-had-played-for-ireland-and-england-1.3819228 |access-date=12 September 2020 |newspaper=The Irish Times |archive-date=10 November 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211110094124/https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/soccer/international/michael-walker-before-declan-rice-only-one-man-had-played-for-ireland-and-england-1.3819228 |url-status=live}}</ref> Rice was named in the [[UEFA Euro 2020 squads#England|England squad]] for [[UEFA Euro 2020]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2021/june/01-june/declan-rice-named-final-england-euro-2020-squad |title=Declan Rice named in final England Euro 2020 squad |publisher=West Ham United F.C.|access-date=1 June 2021|archive-date=3 June 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210603083141/https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2021/june/01-june/declan-rice-named-final-england-euro-2020-squad|url-status=live}}</ref> Rice played in all seven games for England at Euro 2020 where they finished runner-up in the final to [[Italy national football team|Italy]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2021/July/08-July/UEFAEuro2020WestHamUnitedsDeclanRicethroughtothefinal |title=UEFA Euro 2020: West Ham United's Declan Rice through to the final &#124; West Ham United |publisher=West Ham United F.C.|access-date=13 October 2021|archive-date=29 October 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211029175402/https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2021/July/08-July/UEFAEuro2020WestHamUnitedsDeclanRicethroughtothefinal|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2021/July/11-July/WestHamUnitedsDeclanRicewinsUEFAEuropeanChampionship |title=West Ham United's Declan Rice edged out in UEFA European Championship final &#124; West Ham United |publisher=West Ham United F.C.|access-date=13 October 2021|archive-date=29 October 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211029175403/https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2021/July/11-July/WestHamUnitedsDeclanRicewinsUEFAEuropeanChampionship|url-status=live}}</ref>

Rice was included in the England [[2022 FIFA World Cup squads#England|squad]] for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]].<ref name="WC2022">{{cite web |title=Maddison, Rashford and Wilson make England squad |website=BBC Sport |date=10 November 2022 |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/63585869 |access-date=10 November 2022 |archive-date=25 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221125124014/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/63585869 |url-status=live }}</ref> He started all five matches as England reached the quarter-finals, losing 2–1 to [[France national football team|France]].<ref>{{cite web|title=World Cup Player Profile: Rice|website=USA Today|url=https://sportsdata.usatoday.com/soccer/wc/player/204480?team=114&season=2022|access-date=25 March 2023|archive-date=25 March 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230325113933/https://sportsdata.usatoday.com/soccer/wc/player/204480?team=114&season=2022|url-status=live}}</ref>

Ahead of his 50th cap for the senior side, it was announced that Rice would captain England for the first time, against [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]] in March 2024.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://apnews.com/article/england-declan-rice-captain-belgium-6321650aab03d2eeaf0775edde018aee |title=Declan Rice takes England captaincy on 50th appearance and ready to 'deliver history' at Euro 2024 |first=Steve |last=Douglas |website=Associated Press |date=25 March 2024 |access-date=25 March 2024}}</ref>  On 6 June, he was named in England's 26-man squad for [[UEFA Euro 2024]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cv22menk7dno |title=Eze & Wharton named in England squad for Euro 2024 |website=BBC Sport |date=6 June 2024 |access-date=6 June 2024}}</ref> He started in central midfield in the team's opening match against [[Serbia national football team|Serbia]], playing the full 90 minutes as England won 1–0 to go top of [[UEFA Euro 2024 Group C|Group C]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cz992dxd4xwt#Line-ups|title= Serbia 0–1 England|website=BBC Sport|access-date=17 June 2024}}</ref>

==Style of play==
Rice plays predominantly as a defensive midfielder and is known for his athleticism and tackling ability. In more recent times, he has begun to build a reputation as a more complete midfielder due to his ball carrying skills and ability to score goals from range, which has seen him be deployed in a more offensive role on occasion as a [[Midfielder#Box-to-box midfielder|number eight]].<ref name=":3">{{cite news |last1=Bate |first1=Adam |title=Declan Rice has become the complete midfielder at West Ham thanks to scanning, ball carrying and tackling |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11685/12507939/declan-rice-has-become-the-complete-midfielder-at-west-ham-thanks-to-scanning-ball-carrying-and-tackling |website=Sky Sports |date=16 January 2022}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Steinberg |first=Rachael |date=22 October 2022 |title=Declan Rice is best all-around midfielder in England – Gary O'Neil |url=https://uk.style.yahoo.com/declan-rice-best-around-midfielder-080022378.html |archive-date=17 June 2023 |access-date=17 June 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230617065348/https://uk.style.yahoo.com/declan-rice-best-around-midfielder-080022378.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Bate |first=Adam |date=16 January 2022 |title=Declan Rice had become the complete midfielder |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11685/12507939/declan-rice-has-become-the-complete-midfielder-at-west-ham-thanks-to-scanning-ball-carrying-and-tackling |archive-date=17 June 2023 |access-date=17 June 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230617065349/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11685/12507939/declan-rice-has-become-the-complete-midfielder-at-west-ham-thanks-to-scanning-ball-carrying-and-tackling |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=8 June 2023 |title=Declan Rice named UEFA Europa Conference League Player of the Season |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaconferenceleague/news/0282-183500452524-1c503bccb2ed-1000--declan-rice-named-uefa-europa-conference-league-player-of-/ |access-date=17 June 2023 |archive-date=8 June 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230608201525/https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaconferenceleague/news/0282-183500452524-1c503bccb2ed-1000--declan-rice-named-uefa-europa-conference-league-player-of-/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Hodson |first=Tony |title=Declan Rice Tactical Analysis |url=https://www.coachesvoice.com/cv/declan-rice-west-ham-england/ |access-date=17 June 2023 |archive-date=17 June 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230617065349/https://www.coachesvoice.com/cv/declan-rice-west-ham-england/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Oladehinde |first=Stephen |date=7 May 2023 |title=Declan Rice: 5 reasons why Arsenal must sign the English midfielder |url=https://www.pulsesports.ng/football/story/declan-rice-5-reasons-why-arsenal-must-sign-the-english-midfielder-2023050714340739434 |access-date=17 June 2023 |archive-date=17 June 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230617070850/https://www.pulsesports.ng/football/story/declan-rice-5-reasons-why-arsenal-must-sign-the-english-midfielder-2023050714340739434 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Roché |first1=Art de |title=Rice was a defensive No 6 but is fast becoming an attacking No 8 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/5358773/2024/03/30/declan-rice-arsenal-attacker-goals-assists/ |access-date=21 June 2024 |work=The New York Times |date=30 March 2024}}</ref> He has also been praised in the media for his passing ability.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wright |first1=Nick |title=Declan Rice is making an instant impact and driving Arsenal forward following his £105m move from West Ham |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11670/12966462/declan-rice-is-making-an-instant-impact-and-driving-arsenal-forward-following-his-gbp105m-move-from-west-ham |access-date=21 June 2024 |work=Sky Sports |date=24 September 2023}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Rice has been a close friend of [[Mason Mount]] since childhood from when they played together at Chelsea's academy.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Steinberg |first=Jacob |date=29 November 2019 |title=Mason Mount and Declan Rice: 'We're always together. They call us Dumb and Dumber' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/nov/29/mason-mount-declan-rice-chelsea-west-ham-england-childhood-friends |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=19 November 2020 |archive-date=4 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210204070509/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/nov/29/mason-mount-declan-rice-chelsea-west-ham-england-childhood-friends |url-status=live}}</ref> His cousin, [[Finley Munroe]], is also a professional footballer for [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |last=Townley |first=John |date=2024-01-26 |title=Who is Finley Munroe? Declan Rice cousin named in Aston Villa squad vs Chelsea |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/aston-villa-promote-declan-rices-27049103 |access-date=2024-05-09 |website=Birmingham Live |language=en}}</ref>

In March 2019, Rice apologised for pro-[[Irish Republican Army]] comments he made on social media in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/mar/21/declan-rice-apologises-ira-social-media-england|title=Declan Rice apologises over apparent support for IRA on social media |work=The Guardian |date=21 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/12020/11671840/declan-rice-apologises-for-pro-ira-posts-on-social-media|title=Declan Rice apologises for pro-IRA posts on social media|website=Sky Sports|date=21 March 2019}}</ref>

In August 2022, Rice confirmed the birth of his first child, a son, with long-term girlfriend, Lauren Fryer.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hampson |first1=Laura |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/declan-rice-baby-lauren-fryer-b2149823.html |title=Declan Rice quietly confirms birth of first child with Lauren Fryer |access-date=9 June 2023 |newspaper=The Independent |location=London |date=22 August 2022 |archive-date=9 June 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230609022919/https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/declan-rice-baby-lauren-fryer-b2149823.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Rice has a [[tattoo]] of his son's name on his arm.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/declan-rice-lauren-fryer-relationship-31427073|title=Declan Rice's romance with Lauren Fryer and how they beat online trolls|first=Jake|last=Bayliss|date=16 April 2025|website=Wales Online}}</ref> It was reported in 2024 that Fryer had removed posts from her [[Instagram]] account after being subjected to abuse from [[Troll (slang)|online trolls]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/declan-rice-arsenal-girlfriend-lauren-fryer-sexism-football-b2535349.html|title=What the awful abuse of Declan Rice's partner tells us about football|first=Gemma|last=Abbott|date=26 April 2024|website=The Independent}}</ref> Rice responded to the abusive comments by stating: "She is the love of my life and I don't need an upgrade."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gloucestershirelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/declan-rice-arsenal-madrid-girlfriend-10107702|title=Trolling forces Declan Rice's partner Lauren Fryer to have chat with Dani Dyer|first=Chris|last=Burns|date=16 April 2025|website=Gloucestershire Live}}</ref>

